# Using the generated TypeScript client

The TS client lives at `frontend/src/api/` and is regenerated by `just regen`.
Don't edit it by hand.

## Importing

```tsx
import { {{ project_name | pascal_case }}Client, ApiError } from "@/api";
```

The aggregate client exposes one property per service:

```tsx
const client = new {{ project_name | pascal_case }}Client({ baseUrl: "/" });
const g = await client.greeting.createGreeting({
    greeting: { recipient: "world" },
});
```

## Auth + OBO

When the React app runs *inside* Databricks Apps, the platform's edge attaches
`X-Forwarded-Access-Token` automatically — the Rust server handles it via
`RequestContext`. From the browser's perspective, just make plain `fetch` calls.

Locally, the Envoy front-edge component injects the same header from your
`.env.local`, so the same React code path works.

## Error handling

```tsx
try {
    const g = await client.greeting.createGreeting({...});
} catch (e) {
    if (e instanceof ApiError) {
        // e.code is `{{ project_name | screaming_snake_case }}_<...>`
        // e.status is the HTTP status
        // e.message is server-rendered
    }
}
```

## Setting headers

The client builder accepts a `headers` callback for advanced cases (custom
tracing IDs, etc.):

```tsx
const client = new {{ project_name | pascal_case }}Client({
    baseUrl: "/",
    headers: () => ({ "x-request-id": crypto.randomUUID() }),
});
```
